    <statement><p>Simplify this expression, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-36}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-36}}}{{\frac{1}{r+36}}}=}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}, r\ne -36</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-36}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-36}}}{{\frac{1}{r+36}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{r}{r^{2}-36}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-36}}</m> and <m>{\frac{1}{r+36}}</m>, which is <m>{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{r}{r^{2}-36}-\frac{1}{r^{2}-36}}}{{\frac{1}{r+36}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}}}{{\frac{1}{r+36}}} \\
    \amp = \frac{({\frac{r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}-\frac{1}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}})\cdot{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)}}{({\frac{1}{r+36}})\cdot{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)}} \\
    \amp = \frac{{\frac{r}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)-\frac{1}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}\mathopen{}\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)}}{{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}}, r \ne -36 \\
    \amp = \frac{{r\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)-\left(r+36\right)}}{{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}}, r \ne -36\\
    \amp = \frac{{r^{2}+35r-36}}{{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}}, r \ne -36 \\
    \amp = {\frac{\left(r-1\right)\mathopen{}\left(r+36\right)}{\left(r+6\right)\mathopen{}\left(r-6\right)}, r\ne -36}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since <m>r+36</m> was canceled, <m>r \ne -36</m> is a lost domain condition.</p>
<p>Although <m>r-6</m> and <m>r + 6</m> were also canceled, <m>r \ne 6</m> and <m>r \ne -6</m> are not lost domain conditions because they are implied in the solution.</p>
</solution>
